    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about bread and saw the term maillard reaction. can u explain what that actually is and what temp it usually happens at? i keep getting confused between that and caramelization.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a fascinating chemical process, much like when a little bit of a crusty, slightly-burnt-smelling, perfectly roasted piece of bread is made. It's essentially a complex series of chemical reactions between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor and aroma. It typically kicks off when things get warm enough, usually around 280°F (140°C) and higher. Think of it as the flavor-building process, which is different from caramelization, which is just the sugar breaking down on its own.",
      "source": "target",
